sentences: Edward Isaac Bickert,  (November 29, 1932 – February 28, 2019) was a Canadian jazz guitarist.
Edward Isaac Bickert,  (November 29, 1932 – February 28, 2019) was a Canadian jazz guitarist.
Edward Isaac Bickert,  (November 29, 1932 – February 28, 2019) was a Canadian jazz guitarist.
When he was eight years old, he started playing guitar.
During the early 1950s, Bickert worked as a radio engineer in Toronto.
He went on tour during the 1980s with McConnell, Koffman, and Peter Appleyard.
Lofsky was a member of his quartet in the 1980s and 1990s.
Juno Award for Best Jazz Recording, Sackville 4005 with Don Thompson, 1980
Member of the Order of Canada, 1996

Bickert worked with Rob McConnell, a Canadian band leader, jazz trombonist, composer, and arranger, from the 1960s to the 1990s, appearing on records with McConnell starting with 1969's Boss Brass and continuing through 1998's Big Band Christmas.

Bickert worked with Rob McConnell, a Canadian band leader, jazz trombonist, composer, and arranger, from the 1960s to the 1990s, appearing on records with McConnell starting with 1969's Boss Brass and continuing through 1998's Big Band Christmas.
Desmond featured Bickert's playing on the 1974 studio album Pure Desmond, which brought Bickert's playing to the international jazz audience.

The Desmond-Bickert "Canadian Quartet" (featuring bassist Don Thompson drummer Jerry Fuller) was recorded live in concert on several occasions, resulting in the albums The Paul Desmond Quartet - Live (A&M/Horizon), Paul Desmond (Artist House), Like Someone in Love (Telarc), and Edmonton Festival '76 (Gambit).
While Bickert was recording for Concord Records in the 1980s, he was featured on five studio albums by singer Rosemary Clooney.
